2. Data Wrangling

Crime Data from Chicago

The crime of sexual assault of 2017 in Chicago was chosen as the outcome of predict policing. Differing from burglary, incidents of sexual assault are recorded primarily from reports of victims. Many victims of sexual assault do not choose to report the crime for various reasons such as fear and shame, which is the selection bias of this type of crime.

policeDistricts <- 
  st_read("https://data.cityofchicago.org/api/geospatial/fthy-xz3r?method=export&format=GeoJSON") %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102271') %>%
  dplyr::select(District = dist_num)
  
policeBeats <- 
  st_read("https://data.cityofchicago.org/api/geospatial/aerh-rz74?method=export&format=GeoJSON") %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102271') %>%
  dplyr::select(District = beat_num)

bothPoliceUnits <- rbind(mutate(policeDistricts, Legend = "Police Districts"), 
                         mutate(policeBeats, Legend = "Police Beats"))

Creating a fishnet grid

A fishnet was created based on the Chicago boundary. The sexual assault incidents was counted in each grid.

fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary,
               cellsize = 500, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%            # fast way to select intersecting polygons
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = 1:n())
## add a value of 1 to each crime, sum them with aggregate
crime_net <- 
  dplyr::select(S_ASSAULT) %>% 
  mutate(countAssault = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countAssault = replace_na(countAssault, 0),
         uniqueID = 1:n(),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), 
                       size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countAssault), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Count of Sexsual Assault for the fishnet") +
  mapTheme()

Modeling Spatial Features

Here, based on the broken window theory, five categories of data related to the degree of urban decay were selected (abandon Cars,street Lights Out,abandon Buildings, graffiti, sanitation). In addition, the location of liquor stores may also be associated with crime.

For sexual assault, most of the victims are female, so the number of female population aged 15-40 is selected as a predictor. most of the crimes occur in more private living places rather than outdoors, so zoning is also selected as a factor of location type.

## Features
abandonCars <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Service-Requests/311-Service-Requests-Abandoned-Vehicles/3c9v-pnva") %>%
    mutate(year = substr(creation_date,1,4)) %>% filter(year == "2017") %>%
    dplyr::select(Y = latitude, X = longitude) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
    st_transform(st_crs(fishnet)) %>%
    mutate(Legend = "Abandoned_Cars")

3.Feature Engineering

Nearest Neighbor Feature

K nearest neighbor was used to calculate the average distance of nearest features for each grid and for each point feature. The numbers were then joined to the fishnet.

vars_net <- 
  rbind(abandonCars,streetLightsOut,abandonBuildings,
        liquorRetail, graffiti, sanitation) %>%
  st_join(., fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(uniqueID, Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
    full_join(fishnet) %>%
    spread(Legend, count, fill=0) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(-`<NA>`) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    ungroup()
# convinience to reduce length of function names.
st_c    <- st_coordinates
st_coid <- st_centroid

## create NN from abandoned cars
vars_net <-
  vars_net %>%
    mutate(
      Abandoned_Buildings.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(abandonBuildings),3),
      Abandoned_Cars.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(abandonCars),3),
      Graffiti.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(graffiti),3),
      Liquor_Retail.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(liquorRetail),3),
      Street_Lights_Out.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(streetLightsOut),3),
      Sanitation.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(sanitation),3))

The feature of female number and zoning were joined to the fishnet by spatial join.

## Join 2 new features
vars_net_coid <- st_coid(vars_net) %>%
  st_join(Zoning) %>% 
  st_join(female2017) %>% 
  mutate(zone = replace_na(zone_type, "4"),
         female1540 = replace_na(female15_40, 0)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(uniqueID, zone, female1540) %>% 
  st_drop_geometry()


vars_net <- vars_net %>% 
  left_join(vars_net_coid, by = "uniqueID")

4.Spatial Autocorrelation and Spatial Process

Local Morans I

The spatial autocorrelation was tested by using Local Morans I.

## generates warnings from PROJ issues
## {spdep} to make polygon to neighborhoods... 
final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
## ... and neighborhoods to list of weigths
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

# print(final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE)
## see ?localmoran
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countAssault, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet
final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(Assault_Count = countAssault, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

Below is the plot of local Morans I results. Relatively a few urban areas show spatial autocorrelation.

## This is just for plotting
vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Morans I statistics, Sexual Assault"))

5. Modeling and Cross Validation

Cross Validation

Poisson regression was used as the regression model. First lets take a look at the distribution of sexual assault count in the fishnet.

hist(final_net$countAssault, col="grey", breaks = 30, main = "Sexual Assault distribution")

2 regression model were run. One is random k-fold cross validation. Another is cross validation by neighborhood.

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", 
                 "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn",
                 "S_Assault.isSig", "S_Assault.isSig.dist","zone","female1540")

## cv Random k-fold
reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countAssault",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countAssault, Prediction, geometry) %>% 
  mutate(legend = "Random k-fold")

## cv by neighborhoods
reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",                           
  dependentVariable = "countAssault",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countAssault, Prediction, geometry) %>% 
  mutate(legend = 'Spatial cv')
reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = Prediction - countAssault,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countAssault,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process")) %>%
    st_sf()

Model Accuracy

Below is the MAE for both regression. The random k-fold regression performs better than spatial cv regression.

# calculate errors by NEIGHBORHOOD
error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - countAssault, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

error_by_reg_and_fold %>% 
  arrange(desc(MAE))
error_by_reg_and_fold %>%

st_drop_geometry(error_by_reg_and_fold) %>%

    summarize(Mean_MAE = round(mean(MAE), 2),

  kable() %>%

To compare 2 method, the accuracy of both method was compared in each risk level. The result shows that the risk prediction performs much better in the first 3 levels while kernel density performs better in the last 2 levels.

rbind(burg_KDE_sf, burg_risk_sf) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%

  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%

           y = "% of Test Set Burglaries (per model)",

7.Conclusion and Recommendation

I dont recommend this algorithm be put into production for 2 main reasons. First, the new method fails to perform better in the high risk levels. The reason of this might be that the distribution of sexual assault shows really few spatial process according to Local Morans I. The distribution may be just simply related to the population density rather than broken window area or female population. Thats why the kernel density method performs better. Second, sexual assault as a special crime type, is significantly effected by the selection bias (victims willing to report), which may make the reported incidents really random and hard to find the spatial process behind it. From this aspect, the value of this report is the conclusion that sexual assault does not lend itself to prediction by policing prediction algorithms.
